<Layout title="How to Choose Wine" description="A practical guide to selecting wine at shops, restaurants, and online — from reading shelf talkers to navigating wine lists with confidence.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Learn</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">How to Choose Wine (Without the Anxiety)</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 10 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Standing in a wine shop or staring at a restaurant wine list can feel paralyzing. Hundreds of options, cryptic labels, unfamiliar regions — where do you even start? The truth is, choosing wine well is a learnable skill, and it has very little to do with memorizing appellations or vintages.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Start With What You Like</h2>
      <p>This sounds obvious, but most people skip it. Before you worry about regions or producers, get clear on your flavor preferences. Do you gravitate toward:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Rich and bold?</strong> You probably enjoy full-bodied reds with dark fruit — Cabernet Sauvignon, Malbec, Syrah.</li>
        <li><strong>Light and bright?</strong> Think Pinot Noir, Beaujolais (Gamay), or lighter-styled Sangiovese.</li>
        <li><strong>Crisp and refreshing?</strong> Sauvignon Blanc, Albariño, Vermentino, dry Riesling.</li>
        <li><strong>Round and creamy?</strong> Oaked Chardonnay, Viognier, white Burgundy.</li>
        <li><strong>Sweet or off-dry?</strong> Moscato d'Asti, Gewürztraminer, late-harvest Riesling.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Once you know your general preference zone, you can start exploring within it — and occasionally adventuring outside it.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Choosing Wine at a Shop</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Talk to the staff</h3>
      <p>This is the single best thing you can do. Good wine shops hire knowledgeable people who love helping customers find the right bottle. Tell them three things: what you're eating, what style you like, and your budget. They'll narrow it down to 2–3 options. Don't be embarrassed about your budget — great wines exist at every price point.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Read shelf talkers (carefully)</h3>
      <p>Those little cards next to bottles with scores and descriptions? They can be helpful, but take them with a grain of salt. A 92-point score from a major publication means the wine is good, but scores are subjective and skew toward certain styles. More useful than scores are the flavor descriptors — do those sound appealing to you?</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">The $15–$25 sweet spot</h3>
      <p>For everyday wines, this price range delivers the best quality-to-value ratio. Below $10, you're often paying mostly for packaging and distribution. Above $30, you're increasingly paying for prestige and scarcity. In the $15–$25 zone, you get wines from serious producers who are competing on quality.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Choosing Wine at a Restaurant</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">The sommelier is your friend</h3>
      <p>If the restaurant has a sommelier or wine director, use them. Their job is literally to help you have a better experience. Don't just point at a price and hope — describe what you're in the mood for, mention what you're ordering to eat, and give a budget range ("I'm thinking something around $60–$80").</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">The second-cheapest bottle trick</h3>
      <p>Skip it. Restaurants know people default to the second-cheapest option, and some mark that bottle up accordingly. Instead, look for wines from lesser-known regions — they tend to be better values because demand is lower. That Portuguese red or Greek white on the list? Probably a steal.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">By the glass vs. by the bottle</h3>
      <p>By-the-glass is great for exploration and when your table is ordering wildly different dishes. By the bottle is better value if two or more people are drinking the same thing (a standard bottle is about 5 glasses).</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Choosing Wine Online</h2>
      <p>Online buying is excellent for building a collection but tricky for first-time purchases. Some tips:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Buy from specialty retailers</strong> with editorial teams (not just aggregators). Their curated selections and staff picks are usually reliable.</li>
        <li><strong>Read multiple reviews</strong> — don't rely on a single source. Look for consensus across critics.</li>
        <li><strong>Start with mixed cases</strong> — many online shops offer curated cases around a theme. It's a low-risk way to discover new favorites.</li>
        <li><strong>Consider shipping conditions.</strong> Wine is sensitive to heat. Avoid ordering during summer months unless the retailer guarantees cold-chain shipping.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Five Quick Rules</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Don't buy based on the label.</strong> Beautiful packaging doesn't correlate with wine quality.</li>
        <li><strong>Do explore unfamiliar regions.</strong> The best values in wine are always where consumers haven't caught on yet.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't age wine unless you have proper storage.</strong> 95% of wines are made to be enjoyed within 1–3 years of purchase.</li>
        <li><strong>Do keep a simple journal.</strong> Note what you buy, what you think, and whether you'd buy it again. Patterns will emerge fast.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't overthink it.</strong> Wine is agricultural product fermented into a beverage. It's supposed to be fun.</li>
      </ol>
